                         LMLAB
   LOCAL-FIRST VISUALIZATION TOOL FOR LANGUAGE MODELS

lmlab is a web application for visualizing aspects of large
language models without requiring coding for the end-user.
It's primary use is to be used in teaching non-CS students
about language models, and how they work. It is designed
with flexibility and extensibility in mind, relying only on
standard Python ML libraries (transformers/torch) [1].

Existing solutions either require coding, aren't extensible
enough, or require complicated local installation. This is
unfeasible in many university settings, where computer labs
don't offer that kind of flexibility in what's allowed to be
installed, or where users might want to access the tool from
home.

FEATURE SET
    - visualize token probabilities of input sequence using
      DistilGPT2
    - visualize next-token probabilities using DistilGPT2
      and generate text.
    - visualize attention weights using distilBERT

There's a built-in async queue, allowing deployment on less
powerful servers. For reference, with the current DistilGPT2
and DistilBERT, lmlab takes up about ~700MB RAM.

[1] I came to this conclusion after spending hours trying
    to get attention scores from transformers.js, only to
    realize that exporting attention scores was only
    supported for whisper models...

------------------------------------------------------------
EXTENSIBILITY
    If you want to use this you probably want to customize
    it. lmlab is boilerplate code, and should be easily
    extensible if you dare look inside the code. Here's the
    general structure:

    index.html
        contains the front-end. currently written in
        Swedish.
    app.js
        contains the listeners for the frontend -> backend
        communcation.
    server.py
        contains the logic for communicating with models,
        receiving input from the API, and sending data back.

------------------------------------------------------------

DEVELOPING/LOCAL INSTALLATION
    If you just want to run it locally, you can get up and
    running quite easily. Just run the following commands:

        git clone https://github.com/skogsgren/lmlab
        pip3 install -r lmlab/requirements.txt
        fastapi-cli dev lmlab/server.py

    Then you should be able to access it at localhost:8000

DEPLOYING (LINUX)
    Assuming you're fine with the app being located at
    /opt/lmlab, and the user being www-data:

        sudo su
        cd /opt
        git clone https://github.com/skogsgren/lmlab
        python3 -m venv lmlab/venv
        mkdir lmlab/cache
        source lmlab/venv/bin/activate
        pip3 install -r lmlab/requirements.txt
        chown -R www-data:www-data /opt/lmlab

    Then you can test it by running this command:

        /opt/lmlab/venv/bin/gunicorn \
            -k uvicorn.workers.UvicornWorker \
            -w 4 -b 127.0.0.1:8000 server:app

    If everything's working, enable the systemd service:

        ln -s /opt/lmlab/lmlab.service
        systemctl enable lmlab
        systemctl start lmlab

    Check on progress/status by this command:

        systemctl status lmlab

    Don't expose this to the internet carelessly, I haven't
    done any pentesting or such so there may be
    vulnaribilities. Though, if you keep it behind SSH/VPN
    you should be fine (hopefully).

DEPLOYING (WINDOWS)
